{{Infobox Officeholder
| name             = John Harrison O'Donnell
| image            = JohnHODonnell.jpg
| birth_date       = {{birth date|1838|04|07}}
| birth_place      = [[Simcoe, Ontario]]
| death_date       = {{death date and age|1912|10|26|1838|04|07}}
| death_place      = [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]]
| office           = Member of the [[Legislative Council of Manitoba]]
| term             = 1871&ndash;1876
}}

'''John Harrison O'Donnell''' (April 7, 1838 &ndash; October 26, 1912)<ref name="uman">{{cite web |url=http://nanna.lib.umanitoba.ca/icaatom/index.php/odonnell-john-harrison-2;rad |title=O'Donnell, John Harrison |publisher=University of Manitoba |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> was a physician and political figure in [[Manitoba]]. He was a member of the [[Legislative Council of Manitoba]] from 1871 to 1876<ref name="men"/> and served as its speaker in 1875.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hVUvAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA95 |title=A Political Manual of the Province of Manitoba and the North-West Territories |page=95 |year=1887 |last=Robertson |first=John Palmerston |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref>

He was born in [[Simcoe, Ontario|Simcoe]], [[Upper Canada]], the son of John O'Donnell, a native of [[Ireland]], and was educated at [[Victoria University, Toronto|Victoria University]] and [[University of Toronto Faculty of Medicine|Trinity Medical College]]. In 1861, he married Hannah Routledge.<ref name="men">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TWIoAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA412 |title=The Canadian Album: Men of Canada; Or, Success by Example, ... |last=Cochrane |first=William |author2=Hopkins, John Castell |author3=Hunter, W J  |page=412 |year=1891 |volume=Volume 3 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> He practised in [[St. Catharines, Ontario]] and [[Montreal]]<ref name="mhs">{{cite web |url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/people/odonnell_jh.shtml |title=John Harrison O’Donnell (1838-1912) |work=Memorable Manitobans |publisher=Manitoba Historical Society |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> before coming to Manitoba during the [[Red River Rebellion]] of 1869. While helping defend [[John Christian Schultz]]'s property, O'Donnell was taken prisoner. He was a [[justice of the peace]] and made out the arrest warrant for [[Louis Riel]] when the [[Wolseley Expedition]] arrived in 1870. He was the first president of the Provincial Medical Health Board of Manitoba.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SxhaMFMO7eMC&pg=PA208 |title=Manitoba Medicine: A Brief History |page=208 |last=Carr |first=Ian |year=1999 |ISBN=0887553427 |publisher=University of Manitoba Press |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> O'Donnell served as provincial [[coroner]] and helped found the [[Winnipeg General Hospital]]. He was a professor of sanitary science at the Medical College of the [[University of Manitoba]] and served on the council for the University.<ref name="uman"/>

He wrote ''Manitoba as I saw it, from 1869 to date; with flashlights on the First Riel Rebellion'', published in 1909.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/manitobaasisawit00odonuoft |title=Manitoba as I saw it, from 1869 to date; with flashlights on the First Riel Rebellion |last=O'Donnell |first=John H |year=1909 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref>

He died in Winnipeg at the age of 74.<ref name="deaths">{{cite web |url=http://vitalstats.gov.mb.ca/Query.php |title=Genealogy Searches for Unrestricted Records |publisher=Government of Manitoba |at=Registration number 1912-005379 |accessdate=2013-12-21}}</ref>

